Here are both approaches for .NET MAUI Shell navigation:

**1. Passing a simple string ID**

```csharp
// ProductListPage.xaml.cs or ViewModel
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"ProductDetailsPage?productId={product.Id}");
}
```

**2. Passing the full object via dictionary**

```csharp
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    var parameters = new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("ProductDetailsPage", parameters);
}
```

**Receiving both on the ViewModel with `IQueryAttributable`:**

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    private string _productId;
    private Product _product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1: simple string parameter
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var id))
        {
            _productId = id.ToString();
            // Load full product from a service, DB, etc.
        }

        // Approach 2: full object (passed via dictionary overload)
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product product)
        {
            _product = product;
            _productId = product.Id;
        }
    }
}
```

**Wire up the route and BindingContext:**

```csharp
// In MauiProgram.cs or AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("ProductDetailsPage", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));

// In ProductDetailsPage.xaml.cs
public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = vm;
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Dictionary object |
|---|---|---|
| **GoToAsync overload** | URI query string | `IDictionary<string, object>` |
| **Received as** | `object` (string at runtime) | Original CLR object |
| **Deep-link safe** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No (object not serializable in URI) |
| **Use when** | Simple IDs, filters | You already have the object in memory |

`ApplyQueryAttributes` is called **once** after navigation, before the page appears — so it's the right place to kick off any async loading too (fire-and-forget or via `IAsyncRelayCommand`).
